### Description

When using performance strategy for dataGroup there is no way to switch strategy for a specific request (ie: force freshness for one request) . This is a common use case when you know the data has been updated and you want the latest version without waiting for max-age .



### Proposed solution

handleFetchWithFreshness when Cache-Control says the value might be stale the same way it is done for AssetGroup

### Alternatives considered

Use some other header like `ngsw-strategy=freshness` or `ngsw-strategy=performance` to have the ability to switch for specific edge cases.

Very ugly **Workaround** for now a SkipCacheInterceptor that based one the header removes the cache and reinstate it if the request fails:

```
@Injectable()
export class SkipCacheInterceptor implements HttpInterceptor {
  constructor(private offlineModeService: OfflineModeService) {}

  intercept(request: HttpRequest<any>, next: HttpHandler): Observable<HttpEvent<any>> {
    // add skip cache logic only if request asks for skip cache and for now works only GET method
    if (request.method === 'GET' && request.headers.has('skip-cache')) {
      return from(this.offlineModeService.getCachedResponse(request.urlWithParams)).pipe(
        switchMap(cachedResponse => {
          if (cachedResponse) {
            const url = request.urlWithParams;
            return from(caches.open(DATA_CACHE_NAME)).pipe(
              switchMap(cache => cache.delete(url)),
              switchMap(() => next.handle(request)),
              catchError(() =>
                from(caches.open(DATA_CACHE_NAME)).pipe(
                  // on error put back previous response in cache and use it
                  switchMap(cache => cache.put(url, cachedResponse)),
                  switchMap(() => this.buildHttpResponseFromCachedResponse(cachedResponse, url))
                )
              )
            );
          } else {
            return next.handle(request);
          }
        })
      );
    }
    return next.handle(request);
  }

  private buildHttpResponseFromCachedResponse(cachedResponse: Response, url: string): Observable<HttpResponse<any>> {
    const headers = new HttpHeaders();
    cachedResponse.headers.forEach((v, k) => headers.append(k, v));
    return from(cachedResponse.json()).pipe(
      map(
        body => new HttpResponse<any>({
          body,
          headers,
          url,
          status: cachedResponse.status,
          statusText: cachedResponse.statusText,
        })
      )
    )
  }
}
```

